<div id="review_2081487884" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2081487884" />
    <a title="Gerry" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18688312-gerry"><img alt="Gerry" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1488530482p2/18688312.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2081487884?book_show_action=true">Aug 03, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gerry" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gerry" href="/user/show/18688312-gerry">Gerry</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18688312-gerry?shelf=civil-war">civil-war</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18688312-gerry?shelf=19th-century">19th-century</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2081487884" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17059720116248272314">This is mainly the story of a company of Confederate soldiers in the Stonewall Brigade during the 1862 campaign from Cedar Mountain through Antietam. The supporting cast includes one soldier’s family, two civilians passing information to Union authorities, and Stonewall Jackson himself. Abraham Lincoln has a cameo, too. There is no great derring-do here; just ordinary people trying to get by as best they can, and there is little to see of grand strategy. The dialogue seems real enough; this writ</span>
  <span id="freeText17059720116248272314" style="display:none">This is mainly the story of a company of Confederate soldiers in the Stonewall Brigade during the 1862 campaign from Cedar Mountain through Antietam. The supporting cast includes one soldier’s family, two civilians passing information to Union authorities, and Stonewall Jackson himself. Abraham Lincoln has a cameo, too. There is no great derring-do here; just ordinary people trying to get by as best they can, and there is little to see of grand strategy. The dialogue seems real enough; this writer is no language expert and author Keneally is Australian (at least, there were no “g’day mates” in the story). He has General Lee calling General Longstreet “Jimmie”; Longstreet went by “Peter,” and General Lee himself rarely used his subordinates’ given names (Harry Heth being a rare exception). But I quibble. The story is an enjoyable read, the characters are realistic and human, and deserve sympathy. There are no real bad guys. The account of Antietam was especially good. And grim.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17059720116248272314" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

