<div id="review_3862272820" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3862272820" />
    <a title="Eric O&#39;Brien" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2837715-eric-o-brien"><img alt="Eric O&#39;Brien" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1614416272p2/2837715.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3862272820?book_show_action=true">Feb 27, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eric O&#39;Brien" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eric O&#39;Brien" href="/user/show/2837715-eric-o-brien">Eric O&#39;Brien</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3862272820" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer622679989859454134">I get on historical fiction benders, sometimes about the US Civil War. After finishing Killer Angels, I wanted another book about the war, and Confederates depicts the rank and file soldier, war correspondent, and spy. But it does not glamorize the Confederate cause, as the title might imply. Yes, Jackson is a point of view character, one realized as vividly and humanly as Longstreet or Chamberlin in Shaara. But other protagonists include a nurse who is providing intelligence to the Union, a Nor</span>
  <span id="freeText622679989859454134" style="display:none">I get on historical fiction benders, sometimes about the US Civil War. After finishing Killer Angels, I wanted another book about the war, and Confederates depicts the rank and file soldier, war correspondent, and spy. But it does not glamorize the Confederate cause, as the title might imply. Yes, Jackson is a point of view character, one realized as vividly and humanly as Longstreet or Chamberlin in Shaara. But other protagonists include a nurse who is providing intelligence to the Union, a Northerner who is conscripted into the Army of Northern Virginia, and a English aristocrat who spies for Stanton. <br /><br />Keneally wrote Schindler’s List. That same sense of nobility amidst evil is a feature in Confederates. </span>
  <a data-text-id="622679989859454134" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


